{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496652"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:52:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:52:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1401"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1401"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.61,0.06,0.06,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1401"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80379"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1401"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1401"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65648"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"156"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1595"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27473"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42306"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44341"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80379"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 29-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of headache, fever and confusion. Her partner reports that she has become increasingly confused over the past 24 hours and is avoiding bright lights due to headache exacerbation. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 110/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 38.6\u00b0C. She is markedly photophobic with significant nuchal rigidity. She is oriented to person only.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELumbar puncture reveals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EOpening pressure: 18 cmH2O (10-20)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count: 80 x 10^6/L (\u22645), predominantly mononuclear cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EProtein: 0.7 g/L (0.18-0.45)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGlucose: 3.0 mmol/L (2.5-3.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGram stain: No organisms seen\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely causative organism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Neisseria meningitidis","Herpes simplex virus","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Varicella zoster virus","Cryptococcus gattii"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of meningoencephalitis, characterized by fever, headache, photophobia, neck stiffness, and importantly, altered mental status. The CSF profile shows a lymphocytic pleocytosis with mildly elevated protein and normal glucose, typical of viral meningoencephalitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes simplex virus\u003C/strong\u003E (HSV) is the most common cause of sporadic viral encephalitis in immunocompetent adults. The presence of confusion is particularly suggestive of HSV encephalitis, which has a predilection for affecting the temporal lobes. Early recognition and treatment with acyclovir is crucial to prevent severe neurological sequelae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeisseria meningitidis\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes bacterial meningitis with a more dramatic CSF profile including markedly elevated white cell count (\u003E1000) with neutrophil predominance, very high protein, and low glucose. The Gram stain would likely show Gram-negative diplococci.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/strong\u003E, like \u003Cem\u003EN. meningitidis\u003C/em\u003E, causes bacterial meningitis with similar CSF findings and would typically show Gram-positive diplococci on Gram stain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaricella zoster virus\u003C/strong\u003E can cause meningoencephalitis but is less common than HSV and typically occurs in the context of shingles or chickenpox.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryptococcus gattii\u003C/strong\u003E causes fungal meningitis which typically occurs in immunocompromised patients or those with specific exposures. The CSF glucose would typically be lower, and India ink stain or cryptococcal antigen would be positive.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Herpes simplex virus is the most common cause of viral meningoencephalitis in immunocompetent adults.","CSF findings in viral meningitis typically show lymphocytic pleocytosis, mildly elevated protein, and normal glucose.","Confusion and altered mental status suggest encephalitis rather than pure meningitis."],"references":["eTG complete [Internet]. Melbourne (Vic): Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd; 2019. Encephalitis [updated 2020 Mar; cited 2021 Feb 15]. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/viewTopic?topicfile=encephalitis#toc_d1e76","eTG complete [Internet]. Melbourne (Vic): Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd; 2019. Meningitis [updated 2020 Mar; cited 2021 Feb 15]. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/viewTopic?topicfile=meningitis","Life in the fast lane [Internet]. CSF analysis. 2020 [updated 2020 Nov; cited 2020 Feb 15]. Available from: https://litfl.com/csf-analysis/","The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne Clinical Practice Guidelines [Internet]. CSF interpretation. 2019 [updated 2019 Aug; cited 2020 Feb 15]. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/CSF_interpretation/","Seehusen DA, Reeves M, Fomin D. Cerebrospinal fluid analysis. American family physician. 2003 Sep 15;68(6):1103-8."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65648"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1401"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65648"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-20T15:08:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-20T15:09:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1401"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80379"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"de